1. Functional Requirements

These describe what the system must do:

The system should accept a URL as input from the user.
The system should check for suspicious keywords in the URL.
The system should detect if the URL contains numeric characters.
The system should verify whether the URL length exceeds a defined limit (e.g., 40 characters).
The system should check if the URL uses HTTPS protocol.
The system should display warning messages for each detected issue.
The system should classify the URL as:
Safe, or
Fraudulent (unsafe)
The system should display a final decision:
“Access Granted” for safe links
“Access Blocked” for suspicious links
2. Non-Functional Requirements

These describe how the system should perform:

Performance:
The program should analyze the URL instantly (low execution time).
Usability:
The interface should be simple (console-based input/output).
Reliability:
The system should consistently produce the same result for the same input.
Maintainability:
The code should be easy to update (e.g., adding more keywords).
Portability:
The program should run on any system with a C++ compiler.
3. Software Requirements
Programming Language: C++
Compiler: Any standard C++ compiler (e.g., GCC, MSVC, Clang)
Libraries Used:
<iostream> (for input/output)
<string> (for string handling)
<cctype> (for isdigit() function)
4. Hardware Requirements
A computer/laptop with:
Minimum 2 GB RAM
Any modern processor
Keyboard for input and display screen for output
5. Input Requirements
A valid URL string entered by the user
Example:
https://example.com
http://free-bonus123.com
6. Output Requirements
Warning messages (if applicable), such as:
Contains suspicious keywords
Contains numbers
URL too long
Not using HTTPS
Final result:
Safe Link (Access Granted) OR
Fraud Link Detected (Access Blocked)
7. Constraints
The system uses rule-based logic only (no AI/ML).
Detection accuracy depends on predefined rules.
May produce:
False positives (safe link flagged unsafe)
False negatives (unsafe link marked safe)
